For each question in COVID, a pie chart could be used.

Use the first question as example:

C1 <- dat1 %>% select(191:193)
level_number <- c(1,0,2,333)
for (i in 1:3){
  C1[,i] <- as.factor(C1[,i])
  levels(C1[,i]) <- level_number[1:length(levels(C1[,i]))]
  C1[,i] <-as.numeric(as.character(C1[,i]))
}
myPalette <- brewer.pal(4, "Blues") 
pie(table(C1[,1]) , labels = c("yes","no","symptom","Not sure"), col=myPalette,
    main="e.g. Have you been diagnosed with Covid-19?")

For Health data, a grouped bar chart could be used.

H1 <- dat1 %>% select(194:202)
level_number <- c("not sure","no","yes")
for (i in 1:9){
  H1[,i] <- as.factor(H1[,i])
  levels(H1[,i]) <- level_number[1:length(levels(H1[,i]))]
}
H11 <- gather(H1,"health","condition")
H12<- H11 %>% count(health,condition)
ggplot(H12, aes(fill=condition, y=n, x=health)) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity") +
  scale_fill_manual("condition", values = c("no" = "slategray", "not sure" = "thistle", "yes" = "slateblue"))

# only show yes option
H13 <- H12 %>% filter(condition =="yes")
ggplot(H13, aes(fill=condition, y=n, x=health)) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity",fill = "slateblue")

For COVID-D/-H/-S/-F/-Q, the ratio could be presented using density function/histogram.

Use COVID-D as example:

C2 <- dat1 %>% select(204:210)
C2 <- C2 %>% mutate(count_total_number=rowSums(.!=0)) %>% 
  mutate(total_score=rowSums(.[1:7])-count_total_number) %>%
  mutate(ave_stress=total_score/count_total_number)
C2$ave_stress <- C2$ave_stress 
# ignore NA
# density
H21 <- C2 %>% filter(!is.na(ave_stress))
ggplot(H21, aes(x=ave_stress)) +
  geom_density(fill="#69b3a2", color="#e9ecef", alpha=0.8)

# histogram
p <- ggplot(H21, aes(x=ave_stress)) + 
  geom_histogram()
p

Sum the COVID-PSYCH/-POSITIVE/-STRESS/-CHECKING

Use COVID-PSYCH as example:

C3 <- dat1 %>% select(241:247) %>%
  mutate(total_score = rowSums(.[1:7]))

# potential relationship between age and COVID-Psych as example
dat2 <- bind_cols(dat1$Age,C3$total_score)
## New names:
## * NA -> ...1
## * NA -> ...2
colnames(dat2) <- c("age","score")
lm1 <- lm(score~age, dat2) 
summary(lm1)

Covid-Action could use radar chart to see which action is most frequent.

C4 <- dat1 %>% select(264:277)
C4 <- C4 %>% mutate(Social_support=rowSums(.[8:11])/3 )%>%
  mutate(Regularity=rowSums(.[12:13]/2)) %>%
  select(-8:-13)
# rename
colnames(C4) <- c("Precaution","Information seeking","Information overconsuming",
                  "Hobbies","Comfort seeking","Prosocial behaviors","Helped by agencies",
                  "Dysfunctional Coping","Social support","Regularity")
C41 <- C4 %>% summarise_each(mean)
